"n./v. 重击，猛打 【英】 v./n.重击，猛打 (to hit with force) 【记】 分割记忆：wall(墙)+ lop(修剪) 【例】 He walloped the ball out of the park. v. /n. (连续用坚硬的拳头)重击, 猛打 【记】有人要wallop你, 你就gallop(v /n 疾驰) 【记】源自gallop 疾驰，g=gu=w；wall墙 + lope跑→向墙跑→撞墙→重击 wallop (v.)  late 14c., ""to gallop,"" possibly from Old North French *waloper (13c., Old French galoper), from Frankish compound *walalaupan ""to run well"" (compare Old High German wela ""well,"" see well (adv.); and Old Low Franconian loupon ""to run, leap,"" from Proto-Germanic *hlaupan; see leap (v.)). The meaning ""to thrash"" (1820) and the noun meaning ""heavy blow"" (1823) may be separate developments, of imitative origin. Related: Walloped; walloping."
